how we can take our data analysis results

00:01:54.440 --> 00:01:57.800
and create talking points, again, in text form

00:01:57.800 --> 00:02:00.080
that we can use to communicate those results.

00:02:01.400 --> 00:02:04.959
So wanted to talk a little bit first about Gemini.

00:02:05.879 --> 00:02:06.760
So to be clear here,

00:02:06.760 --> 00:02:09.279
like we use the word Gemini to refer to many things,

00:02:09.279 --> 00:02:12.039
including the chatbot formerly known as BARD,

00:02:12.039 --> 00:02:14.919
which Laura featured in her last presentation.

00:02:16.039 --> 00:02:18.880
But the point I'm gonna talk about

00:02:18.880 --> 00:02:20.800
is actually the underlying model,

00:02:20.800 --> 00:02:22.399
which can be called via an API,

00:02:22.399 --> 00:02:25.160
which is what I'll demonstrate in the examples here.

00:02:25.160 --> 00:02:26.399
So key things to know about Gemini,

00:02:26.399 --> 00:02:28.039
it's natively multimodal.

00:02:28.039 --> 00:02:30.600
That means it can take into not just text,

00:02:30.600 --> 00:02:34.240
but also video, audio, images,

00:02:34.240 --> 00:02:35.839
and even things kind of like PDFs,

00:02:35.839 --> 00:02:38.199
which are combinations of some of those things.

00:02:38.199 --> 00:02:39.919
And obviously that makes it very powerful

00:02:39.919 --> 00:02:41.199
from an input standpoint.

00:02:41.199 --> 00:02:43.600
Sophisticated reasoning, it can then take those inputs

00:02:43.600 --> 00:02:45.080
and then you can ask questions like,

00:02:45.080 --> 00:02:48.960
hey, given this question and this audio and video,

00:02:48.960 --> 00:02:51.199
give me a summary of these.

00:02:51.199 --> 00:02:53.479
So one kind of interesting use case I had for this

00:02:53.479 --> 00:02:54.679
that worked pretty well,

00:02:54.679 --> 00:02:55.839
I was gonna go on a podcast,

00:02:56.279 --> 00:02:58.039
this was a couple of months ago.

00:02:58.039 --> 00:02:59.199
I was really excited to go on.

00:02:59.199 --> 00:03:01.600
They have a weekly podcast about sports analytics.

00:03:01.600 --> 00:03:03.479
I like sports analytics.

00:03:03.479 --> 00:03:05.000
And I listened to the podcast,

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:06.240
but I don't know what they're talking about.

00:03:06.240 --> 00:03:07.320
And I was like, how can I prep?

00:03:07.320 --> 00:03:09.479
Well, I'll listen to the last few episodes.

00:03:09.479 --> 00:03:11.759
Well, it's an hour per episode.

00:03:11.759 --> 00:03:13.759
I don't necessarily have all that time.

00:03:13.759 --> 00:03:15.520
So what I did was I downloaded the files

00:03:15.520 --> 00:03:18.600
from the last four episodes, put them into Gemini.

00:03:18.600 --> 00:03:20.440
I gave it a pretty sophisticated prompt,

00:03:20.440 --> 00:03:23.080
like, hey, give me some questions you might expect.

00:03:23.080 --> 00:03:24.279
What are some things they talk about?

00:03:24.279 --> 00:03:25.119
They have multiple hosts.

00:03:25.160 --> 00:03:26.600
What are their personalities like?

00:03:26.600 --> 00:03:27.960
And within a minute or two,

00:03:27.960 --> 00:03:31.600
I actually had a really good summary of what they do

00:03:31.600 --> 00:03:33.119
and what I might expect.

00:03:33.119 --> 00:03:35.039
And then, of course, I could ask for timestamps

00:03:35.039 --> 00:03:36.839
and go back and listen if there were particular parts

00:03:36.839 --> 00:03:39.240
that were interesting to me, right?

00:03:39.240 --> 00:03:40.839
So that's a kind of example.

00:03:40.839 --> 00:03:42.639
And the other thing with Gemini

00:03:42.639 --> 00:03:44.960
is we have a robust ecosystem of other tools

00:03:44.960 --> 00:03:48.440
to help with things like retrieval, augmented generation,

00:03:48.440 --> 00:03:50.039
tuning, evaluation.

00:03:50.039 --> 00:03:52.639
I won't get into those, but it's good to know those.

00:03:53.600 --> 00:03:55.759
So one more sort of thing on Gemini.

00:03:55.759 --> 00:03:58.119
The current version of Gemini, we have two different models.

00:03:58.119 --> 00:03:59.279
Again, we're talking about models

00:03:59.279 --> 00:04:02.080
you can call via API, integrate into your workflows.

00:04:02.080 --> 00:04:05.720
Gemini 1.5 Flash and Gemini 1.5 Pro.

00:04:05.720 --> 00:04:07.679
The key thing with Flash is it's fastest,

00:04:07.679 --> 00:04:10.000
it's the most cost-efficient, low latency.

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:12.360
So when you have a task where you want to make a lot of calls

00:04:12.360 --> 00:04:13.679
and you want answers pretty fast,

00:04:13.679 --> 00:04:16.600
Flash is probably the key.

00:04:16.600 --> 00:04:18.000
And Pro, on the other hand,

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:21.279
is sort of the bigger, more top-tier model.

00:04:21.600 --> 00:04:23.640
It can have advanced reasoning

00:04:23.640 --> 00:04:26.079
and you want to do it over vast amounts of data.

00:04:26.079 --> 00:04:27.279
A couple of things to point out here

00:04:27.279 --> 00:04:30.399
when I say cost-efficient for Gemini 1.5 Flash.

00:04:30.399 --> 00:04:32.359
As of this week, it's 50% cheaper

00:04:32.359 --> 00:04:35.760
than competing model from OpenAI

00:04:35.760 --> 00:04:38.679
for prompts of standard length.

00:04:38.679 --> 00:04:43.679
And again, very popular for these low latency,

00:04:43.880 --> 00:04:46.839
high throughput tasks.

00:04:46.839 --> 00:04:48.799
And then another thing to point out here

00:04:48.799 --> 00:04:49.920
with the context window,

00:04:49.920 --> 00:04:52.519
both of these context windows are actually enormous.

00:04:52.519 --> 00:04:53.720
And to give you an idea

00:04:53.720 --> 00:04:56.320
of what the 2 million token context window is,

00:04:56.320 --> 00:04:58.679
which is many multiples bigger than most competitors,

00:04:58.679 --> 00:05:02.239
is you can actually put in 1.4 million words of text,

00:05:02.239 --> 00:05:04.359
which is many novels,

00:05:04.359 --> 00:05:07.839
and two hours of video or 22 hours of audio.

00:05:07.839 --> 00:05:10.160
So this was kind of what I was taking advantage of

00:05:10.160 --> 00:05:13.359
with that podcast summarization piece.

00:05:13.359 --> 00:05:14.200
All right, cool.

00:05:14.200 --> 00:05:15.040
Enough about Gemini.

00:05:15.040 --> 00:05:17.600
So let's see how we can take that

00:05:17.600 --> 00:05:19.600
and put it into a place of data science.

00:05:20.320 --> 00:05:23.040
Again, the happier part of Laura's talk for me

00:05:23.040 --> 00:05:23.880
is she used the Olympics.

00:05:23.880 --> 00:05:25.119
I'm also gonna use the Olympics.

00:05:25.119 --> 00:05:27.119
So that part we're aligned on here.

00:05:28.239 --> 00:05:30.559
So this is a sample sort of data science task.

00:05:30.559 --> 00:05:32.640
I thought it would be, again, timely.

00:05:32.640 --> 00:05:34.600
So let's pretend that we're gonna build a model

00:05:34.600 --> 00:05:38.079
to predict Olympic medals won in the Paris Olympics.

00:05:38.079 --> 00:05:40.079
So we have the common medal table.

00:05:40.079 --> 00:05:41.839
This is from Tokyo.

00:05:41.839 --> 00:05:43.320
And we're gonna predict that total column,

00:05:43.320 --> 00:05:46.559
the total number of medals that a country wins.

00:05:46.559 --> 00:05:49.160
We have a few predictors that we think might be useful,

00:05:49.679 --> 00:05:52.119
including their medal share at the previous two Olympics,

00:05:52.119 --> 00:05:56.559
population, GDP, and again, important like host status.

00:05:56.559 --> 00:05:58.239
There's a noted bump that the host country

00:05:58.239 --> 00:06:01.519
usually wins more medals than they do other times.

00:06:01.519 --> 00:06:03.720
So this isn't by any means the most sophisticated model.

00:06:03.720 --> 00:06:04.720
It's not the idea here.

00:06:04.720 --> 00:06:07.679
We can do something much better if we went sport by sport.

00:06:07.679 --> 00:06:10.119
But the idea is to get an idea to show

00:06:10.119 --> 00:06:13.040
like we have multiple predictors of this target

00:06:13.040 --> 00:06:14.399
that we're interested in.

00:06:14.399 --> 00:06:15.760
We'll use an XGBoost model.

00:06:15.760 --> 00:06:17.119
That's the type of model that's pretty good

00:06:17.119 --> 00:06:20.600
for tabular data like this.

00:06:20.600 --> 00:06:22.200
And we might have interactions, right?

00:06:22.200 --> 00:06:24.359
And things that we want to take into account.

00:06:24.359 --> 00:06:26.200
So again, I'm not gonna dwell too much

00:06:26.200 --> 00:06:27.760
on the results of this model.

00:06:27.760 --> 00:06:28.880
I'll have a GitHub notebook.

00:06:28.880 --> 00:06:31.079
I'll put a link up at the end that you can see

00:06:31.079 --> 00:06:33.600
this in very, very good detail.

00:06:33.600 --> 00:06:35.720
But the model looks to be really good

00:06:35.720 --> 00:06:37.359
on the training set, of course,

00:06:37.359 --> 00:06:38.799
but also pretty good on the test set.

00:06:38.799 --> 00:06:42.600
R squared 94% in this context is actually quite good.

00:06:42.600 --> 00:06:45.880
We're off by about two and a half medals per prediction.

00:06:45.880 --> 00:06:49.480
It turns out this is actually a pretty good model.

00:06:49.480 --> 00:06:51.040
And that's kind of my point here.

00:06:51.040 --> 00:06:51.959
Good enough.

00:06:51.959 --> 00:06:53.600
Let's move forward with what we want to do with it,

00:06:53.600 --> 00:06:56.119
which is make predictions.

00:06:56.119 --> 00:06:59.119
So let's talk about the predictions

00:06:59.119 --> 00:07:00.200
and things we can get out.

00:07:00.200 --> 00:07:02.399
So I picked the host country here, France.

00:07:02.399 --> 00:07:04.239
You can see the predictions we have up top.

00:07:04.239 --> 00:07:06.160
We have the medal share translates

00:07:06.160 --> 00:07:07.799
to about 38 total medals.

00:07:07.799 --> 00:07:08.959
And if you rank that prediction

00:07:08.959 --> 00:07:10.839
amongst all the predictions of the countries we have,

00:07:10.839 --> 00:07:12.600
it would rank about sixth.

00:07:12.600 --> 00:07:13.600
So that sounds good.

00:07:14.600 --> 00:07:15.959
But again, for our stakeholders,

00:07:15.959 --> 00:07:17.440
they may want to be like, okay, well, why?

00:07:17.440 --> 00:07:19.679
What contributed to France's predictions?

00:07:19.679 --> 00:07:23.440
So this is what we call a Shapley values plot.

00:07:23.440 --> 00:07:24.399
Some of you may be familiar.

00:07:24.399 --> 00:07:25.480
Some of you may not be.

00:07:25.480 --> 00:07:27.559
Shapley values are a way to basically,

00:07:27.559 --> 00:07:31.000
on an individual sort of example-by-example basis,

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:33.359
take into account how much does each predictor

00:07:33.359 --> 00:07:35.160
contribute to the model output.

00:07:35.160 --> 00:07:37.200
So it takes kind of both the global variable importance

00:07:37.200 --> 00:07:39.320
and also the local variable importance,

00:07:39.320 --> 00:07:41.600
and we can have this sort of waterfall plot showing.

00:07:41.600 --> 00:07:43.320
So the main thing that matters here,

00:07:43.359 --> 00:07:46.480
and in most cases, is actually the last Olympics medal share

00:07:46.480 --> 00:07:47.359
is a really good predictor

00:07:47.359 --> 00:07:48.959
of how well you're gonna do in the next Olympics.

00:07:48.959 --> 00:07:49.880
And in this case, it's France.

00:07:49.880 --> 00:07:52.440
So they get a good bump for being the host country.

00:07:52.440 --> 00:07:53.880
So that's cool.

00:07:53.880 --> 00:07:54.720
I'm a data scientist.

00:07:54.720 --> 00:07:55.559
I got my prediction.

00:07:55.559 --> 00:07:57.160
I got my Shapley values.

00:07:57.160 --> 00:07:58.000
I'm good, right?

00:07:58.000 --> 00:07:59.920
I can just turn this over to some...

00:07:59.920 --> 00:08:01.519
Yeah, I see some people laughing.

00:08:01.519 --> 00:08:04.040
I can't turn this over to someone.

00:08:04.040 --> 00:08:06.519
Most sort of stakeholders, senior folks,

00:08:06.519 --> 00:08:08.519
are not gonna be able to interpret this plot,

00:08:08.519 --> 00:08:11.239
and they're just going to stare at me.

00:08:11.239 --> 00:08:13.959
So what should we do here?

00:08:13.959 --> 00:08:16.040
Well, this is where we can ask Gemini for help.

00:08:16.040 --> 00:08:20.559
So I'm gonna build up this prompt sort of iteratively here.

00:08:20.559 --> 00:08:22.880
I'm gonna put in some details, but not all of them.

00:08:22.880 --> 00:08:24.480
So first, we're gonna...

00:08:24.480 --> 00:08:27.000
So again, Gemini and multimodal, so I can give you that.

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:27.959
I can put in that plot.

00:08:27.959 --> 00:08:30.440
We'll show that in a second, but let's set the stage.

00:08:30.440 --> 00:08:32.640
So you're a data scientist who does a great job

00:08:32.640 --> 00:08:34.760
of explaining various outputs from data analysis

00:08:34.760 --> 00:08:37.159
and modeling, including numbers, tables, and plots

00:08:37.159 --> 00:08:38.679
to help a more general audience

00:08:38.679 --> 00:08:40.320
understand your results better.

00:08:40.320 --> 00:08:41.320
So this is to set the stage.

00:08:41.320 --> 00:08:43.119
We can use this for other parts too.

00:08:44.599 --> 00:08:45.960
Now we get into the specifics here.

00:08:45.960 --> 00:08:47.200
Please use the information below

00:08:47.200 --> 00:08:48.440
in the provided Shapley plot

00:08:48.440 --> 00:08:51.400
to explain France's 2024 medals predictions.

00:08:51.400 --> 00:08:53.640
Put in those predictions, put in that plot.

00:08:53.640 --> 00:08:54.840
Again, it takes into account images,

00:08:54.840 --> 00:08:56.640
so I have the prompt, I have the image.

00:08:57.640 --> 00:08:59.179
There's a few other details I'm leaving out.

00:08:59.179 --> 00:09:01.919
I go very specific on, hey, this part means this.

00:09:01.919 --> 00:09:04.179
Shapley values, which they kinda know.

00:09:05.599 --> 00:09:06.760
This is also key at the bottom.

00:09:06.760 --> 00:09:08.400
Stick to only the data information

00:09:08.400 --> 00:09:09.820
provided in creating a response.

00:09:10.260 --> 00:09:11.099
Your response should be understandable

00:09:11.099 --> 00:09:13.260
by a non-technical audience, 100 words or fewer.

00:09:13.260 --> 00:09:14.260
Obviously you can change that.

00:09:14.260 --> 00:09:17.099
And in English, I have English in red here.

00:09:17.099 --> 00:09:19.400
We'll talk about a change to that in a minute.

00:09:20.460 --> 00:09:23.460
So we do this, we submit it to Gemini,

00:09:23.460 --> 00:09:27.020
and we get, so I have this stuff at the top, the response.

00:09:27.020 --> 00:09:29.659
The model predicts France will win 38.1 medals

00:09:29.659 --> 00:09:32.260
in the 2024 Olympics, ranking them fifth overall.

00:09:32.260 --> 00:09:33.299
The prediction is largely driven

00:09:33.299 --> 00:09:35.380
by France's strong performance in the previous Olympics,

00:09:35.380 --> 00:09:37.340
as well as the fact that they're hosting the games.

00:09:37.340 --> 00:09:39.380
The model also suggests that France's GDP

00:09:39.380 --> 00:09:42.679
has a small positive impact on their medal count.

00:09:42.679 --> 00:09:44.940
I think this is pretty good, right?

00:09:45.940 --> 00:09:47.099
This comes out from the model.

00:09:47.099 --> 00:09:48.780
They took into account the right context.

00:09:48.780 --> 00:09:49.739
It was able to read the plot,

00:09:49.739 --> 00:09:51.299
see which parts were most important,

00:09:51.299 --> 00:09:55.179
and give me a summary of the results with an explanation.

00:09:56.299 --> 00:10:00.320
And this is something where I could potentially

00:10:00.320 --> 00:10:02.700
present this to a stakeholder or include it in a report

00:10:02.700 --> 00:10:04.200
and feel pretty good about it.

00:10:05.299 --> 00:10:07.700
So that's good, we get an explanation in English.

00:10:08.380 --> 00:10:11.659
But we're talking about France.

00:10:11.659 --> 00:10:12.859
And maybe some of the people

00:10:12.859 --> 00:10:15.299
who are interested in this content speak English.

00:10:15.299 --> 00:10:17.080
They speak French.

00:10:17.979 --> 00:10:21.460
So the good thing is Gemini actually knows 40

00:10:21.460 --> 00:10:23.140
and growing number of languages.

00:10:23.140 --> 00:10:25.099
So it's the same long prompt as before,

00:10:25.099 --> 00:10:27.140
and I changed one word, the last one,

00:10:27.140 --> 00:10:29.239
from English to French.

00:10:29.239 --> 00:10:30.140
And what do I get?

00:10:31.979 --> 00:10:36.440
So I don't know French, so I can't tell you exactly here,

00:10:36.440 --> 00:10:38.159
but I did put this back into translate.

00:10:38.159 --> 00:10:40.880
And it's not the same exact response translated,

